      key_facts: "On November 1, 2024, CHP Officers Meza-Gonzalez (#023295) and Melano (#023054) found Plaintiff asleep in a Tesla Model Y parked on the I-580 East shoulder in Livermore. No moving violation was observed. Officer Meza served DS-367 designating a 'Chemical Test Refusal,' triggering administrative license suspension. The DS-367 contains critical internal contradictions: 'Chemical Test Refusal' is checked yet blood was drawn 6.5 hours post-arrest pursuant to warrant WAR913372; the PAS section is entirely blank; no driving was observed; and the DS-367 claims Meza-Gonzalez 'smelled the strong distinct odor of an alcoholic beverage' — directly contradicted by dashcam audio in which Melano identifies the only liquid present as urine. CHP subsequently issued a Detention Certificate (PC §849(b)(1)) formally repudiating the arrest; no criminal charges were filed. At the January 24, 2025 APS hearing, Hearing Officer Candelaria served simultaneously as prosecutor and adjudicator — condemned in Knudsen v. DMV and California DUI Lawyers Ass'n v. DMV — applied an irrebuttable presumption of official regularity, and dismissed the Detention Certificate and binding Mercer v. DMV precedent as 'unpersuasive' without analysis. Plaintiff had started at Centerline Drivers (Lily Transportation–Toyota route, $33.35/hr regular / $50.03/hr premium) on October 30, 2024 — two days before the incident. The CDL suspension (Feb. 20, 2025 – Feb. 19, 2026) caused $226,117 in total economic damages: lost wages $114,894; benefits $28,723; career impact $75,000; out-of-pocket $7,500.",
